---
import ChapterDivider from '../ChapterDivider.astro';
import ReferenceSup from '../ReferenceSup.astro';
import JuvenileJusticeTrendsGraph from '../graphs/JuvenileJusticeTrendsGraph.astro';
---

<ChapterDivider
	id="chapter-history"
	chapter="Chapter 1"
	title="History of Underage Prosecution"
/>

<section id="history" class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-5 py-16 sm:px-6 sm:py-20 md:py-24">
	<article class="space-y-8 text-[1rem] leading-[1.75] text-black sm:space-y-10 sm:text-[1.125rem] sm:leading-[1.85]">

		<p>
			The history of underage prosecution in the United States includes cases where race,
			fear, and public pressure shaped outcomes more than fairness or child welfare. One of
			the starkest examples is the 1958 "Kissing Case" from Monroe, North Carolina
			<ReferenceSup
				number={1}
				href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kissing_Case"
				label="Wikipedia: Kissing Case"
			/>.
		</p>

		<!-- Pull quote -->
		<div class="py-4">
			<div class="mb-6 w-20 border-t-2 border-[#c1121f]"></div>
			<p class="text-[1.35rem] font-bold leading-snug text-black">
				"They just punched us all in the stomach and back and legs. We were hollering and
				screaming. We thought they were going to kill us."
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
		<!-- Subchapter: Sample Case + Statistics            -->
		<!-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
		<h3 id="history-kissing-case" class="pt-8 text-2xl font-bold text-black">
			The Kissing Case and Its Legacy
		</h3>

		<p>
			In October 1958 in Monroe, North Carolina, 9-year-old James Hanover Thompson and
			his 8-year-old friend David "Fuzzy" Simpson were playing with white children when a
			kissing game began. During the game, a white girl, Sissy Sutton, kissed David on the
			cheek first. After she told her parents, police confronted the boys at gunpoint,
			shouting racial epithets and calling them "little rapists". The boys were beaten and
			reportedly threatened again on Halloween by officers dressed as Klansmen
			<ReferenceSup
				number={1}
				href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kissing_Case"
				label="Wikipedia: Kissing Case"
			/>.
		</p>

		<p>
			The children were charged with assault and molestation, found guilty under the
			segregation-era legal system, and sent to a reformatory for what could have been the
			rest of their childhood. Media coverage, NAACP advocacy, and public outrage turned
			the case into an international symbol of injustice. Under mounting pressure, North
			Carolina Governor Luther H. Hodges pardoned both boys on February 13, 1959
			<ReferenceSup
				number={1}
				href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kissing_Case"
				label="Wikipedia: Kissing Case"
			/>.
		</p>

		<figure class="space-y-3">
			<img
				src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/47/Kissing_Case.jpg"
				alt="James Hanover Thompson and David Simpson after the failed hearing in the Kissing Case"
				class="w-full rounded-md border border-black/10"
				loading="lazy"
			/>
			<figcaption class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-black/60">
				Picture of the boys after the failed hearing.
				<ReferenceSup
					number={2}
					href="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/47/Kissing_Case.jpg"
					label="Wikimedia Commons upload: Kissing_Case.jpg"
				/>
			</figcaption>
		</figure>

		<!-- Statistics block -->
		<div class="rounded-md border border-black/10 bg-white p-6">
			<p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-black/40">Key Statistics</p>
			<ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-base text-black">
				<li>46 states and the District of Columbia had laws that enabled transfer of juveniles to adult criminal court <ReferenceSup number={4} href="https://ojjdp.ojp.gov/sites/g/files/xyckuh176/files/pubs/tryingjuvasadult/transfer.html" label="OJJDP: Trying Juveniles as Adults (State Transfer Laws)" />.</li>
				<li>Most transfer laws were expanded during and after the 1990s "superpredator" panic, even though youth crime trends later declined <ReferenceSup number={3} href="https://jjie.org/2017/02/27/juvenile-justice-reforms-went-backwards-in-the-90s/" label="JJIE: Juvenile Justice Reforms Went Backwards in the '90s" />.</li>
				<li>Current reform efforts in several states are aimed at narrowing automatic transfer and restoring age-appropriate adjudication pathways <ReferenceSup number={3} href="https://jjie.org/2017/02/27/juvenile-justice-reforms-went-backwards-in-the-90s/" label="JJIE: Juvenile Justice Reforms Went Backwards in the '90s" />.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<!-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
		<!-- Subchapter: Current Prosecution                 -->
		<!-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
		<h3 id="history-current-prosecution" class="pt-8 text-2xl font-bold text-black">
			Current Prosecution
		</h3>

		<p>
			Later, the mid-1990s peak in violent crime fueled a "superpredator" scare that helped
			justify laws treating more juveniles like adults. That prediction did not materialize,
			but many of the laws remained in place long after the panic subsided
			<ReferenceSup
				number={3}
				href="https://jjie.org/2017/02/27/juvenile-justice-reforms-went-backwards-in-the-90s/"
				label="JJIE: Juvenile Justice Reforms Went Backwards in the '90s"
			/>.
		</p>

		<p>
			This trend view tracks major juvenile-justice indicators indexed to 2019 levels and helps
			show how policy-era shifts played out across arrests, delinquency case volumes, and
			detention patterns over time<ReferenceSup number={9} href="https://www.aecf.org/blog/what-juvenile-justice-data-reveal-and-what-the-numbers-cant-tell-us" label="Annie E. Casey Foundation: What juvenile justice data reveal and what the numbers can’t tell us" />.
		</p>

		<JuvenileJusticeTrendsGraph />

		<p>
			Department of Justice reporting on transfer policies shows how broad those laws became,
			and why current crime trends and reform debates are still reacting to that era's policy
			choices <ReferenceSup number={4} href="https://ojjdp.ojp.gov/sites/g/files/xyckuh176/files/pubs/tryingjuvasadult/transfer.html" label="OJJDP: Trying Juveniles as Adults (State Transfer Laws)" />.
		</p>

	</article>
</section>
